<h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<section class="faq" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/FAQPage">

  <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">Will my existing KDP books stop working after the September deadline?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <div itemprop="text">
        <p>No. Books that are already published on KDP will remain live and available for purchase. The mandate applies only to new title submissions and content updates to existing books. If you submitted a book in DOCX in July 2026, it stays published. But if you want to fix a typo or update the cover in October 2026, you will need to upload an EPUB version.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">Can Kindle Create generate valid EPUB for KDP?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <div itemprop="text">
        <p>Yes. Kindle Create added native EPUB export in July 2026. You can import your manuscript as DOCX, use Kindle Create's preview tools to verify layout on multiple Kindle device profiles, then export directly to EPUB. The resulting file meets KDP's EPUB validation requirements. This is Amazon's recommended path for authors who do not want to manage EPUB files manually.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">Does KDP accept EPUB with embedded fonts or advanced CSS?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <div itemprop="text">
        <p>KDP supports standard EPUB 3 features, including embedded fonts, CSS styling, SVG images, and MathML. However, Amazon's Kindle rendering engine (which converts EPUB to KFX internally) has known quirks with some CSS properties. Test your EPUB by previewing it in Kindle Previewer before submitting. Avoid overly complex CSS layouts, CSS Grid, or JavaScript-based interactions — these are not supported in the Kindle ecosystem.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">Can I still submit a PDF for paperback or hardcover?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <div itemprop="text">
        <p>Yes. The EPUB-only mandate applies only to Kindle ebook submissions through KDP. KDP paperback and hardcover submissions still require PDF format with Amazon's specific trim size and bleed settings. The two submission pipelines are separate: EPUB for Kindle ebooks, PDF for print-on-demand books.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
    <h3 itemprop="name">What if my EPUB fails KDP validation?</h3>
    <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
      <div itemprop="text">
        <p>KDP runs a validation check on every EPUB submission. If it fails, Amazon returns an error message identifying the issue — typically missing XHTML files, broken navigation documents, or invalid OPF metadata. Most failures are resolved by opening the EPUB in Sigil 2.8, running Tools → Validate EPUB (epubcheck), and fixing the flagged errors. Calibre can also fix common structural issues via the Polish Books tool's EPUB optimization mode.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

</section>

      `}/>
    </article>
